{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510182"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11502"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.11,0.05,0.03,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62165"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42616"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two hour history of rapid onset central crushing chest pain. His medical history includes peripheral artery disease and type 2 diabetes mellitus. He has a twenty pack-year smoking history and consumes two glasses of wine a day. On examination he is in considerable pain, with a blood pressure of 84/46 mmHg, pulse 72/min, temperature 37.2C and Sa02 of 94% on room air. His jugular venous pressure is elevated. Cardiac auscultation does not reveal any abnormalities and lung auscultation is clear with equal air entry. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sublingual nitroglycerin","Streptokinase","Noradrenaline","Atenolol","IV fluid bolus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA right ventricular (RV) infarction should be considered in all patients who present with an acute inferior-wall myocardial infarction (MI), especially in the setting of hypotension. The clinical vignette above is strongly suggestive of acute coronary syndrome and requires immediate ECG monitoring and troponin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows sinus rhythm with a rate of 72/min and a normal axis. The ECG is significant for ST-elevation in leads II, III and aVF, slight ST elevation in leads 5 and 6 with ST depression in the lateral leads I and aVL. This concordant lead involvement is indicative of an inferior-wall myocardial infarction due to occlusion of the right coronary artery. Tall R waves in V1 and V2 are consistent with right ventricular ischaemia, however confirmation of RV infarction requires ST-segment elevation in the specially placed V4R lead. Other supportive features of RV infarction in this ECG include ST  elevation in III more than in II, as well as marked ST depression in V2 without a relatively unremarkable ST segment in V1. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to recognise RV infarction due to its higher association with hypotension, bradycardia requiring pacing support, and in-hospital mortality in comparison to isolated inferior infarction. Approximately 40-50% of patients with an inferior MI have ischaemic RV involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVolume loading with \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E is first-line therapy for RV infarction complicated by hypotension. This is to increase venous return and preload, thus increasing RV filling pressures and myocardial stretch. This consequently utilises the Frank-Starling law to increase stroke volume and subsequently cardiac output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin \u003C/strong\u003Eis contraindicated in this patient due to the presence of hypotension and the strong suspicion of an inferior myocardial infarct. If nitroglycerin was to be given in the setting of a RV infarct, there will be a higher risk of worsening hypotension. A recent meta-analysis suggests that nitrates do not put these patients at increased risk of hypotension - however in this case, the patient is hypotensive and this issues needs to be dealt with first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptokinase \u003C/strong\u003Eis a type of fibrinolytic which forms a complex with plasminogen to convert to plasmin, this process leads to a lysis of fibrin clots. It may be used in situations where percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is unavailable within 120 minutes of presentation and should be given within 30 minutes of hospital arrival if so. This may be the next step in definitive management of the case presented however priority remains in increasing preload through a fluid bolus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline \u003C/strong\u003Eis a sympathomimetic with strong alpha-adrenoreceptor affinity and thus a strong vasoconstriction effect. Fluid resuscitation is first-line prior to vasopressor therapy for managing hypotension in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol \u003C/strong\u003Eis an oral beta-blocker which acts by reducing the sympathetic drive to the heart and thus lowers heart rate, blood pressure and cardiac contractility. Thus, it is completely inappropriate for the clinical case presented.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right ventricular infarction is a life-threatening complication that may accompany inferior myocardial infarction","Nitrates may worsen hypotension associated with inferior myocardial infarcts"],"references":["Snygg J, Bech-Hanssen O, L\u00f6nn L, Andersson B, Aneman A. Fluid therapy in acute myocardial infarction: evaluation of predictors of volume responsiveness. Acta Anaesthesiol Scand. 2009 Jan;53(1):26-33. doi: 10.1111/j.1399-6576.2008.01824.x. Epub 2008 Nov 11. PMID: 19032557.","Robichaud L, Ross D, Proulx MH, L\u00e9gar\u00e9 S, Vacon C, Xue X, Segal E. Prehospital Nitroglycerin Safety in Inferior ST Elevation Myocardial Infarction. Prehosp Emerg Care. 2016;20(1):76-81. doi: 10.3109/10903127.2015.1037480. Epub 2015 May 29. PMID: 26024432.","Wilkinson-Stokes M, Betson J, Sawyer S. Adverse events from nitrate administration during right ventricular myocardial infarction: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Emerg Med J. 2023 Feb;40(2):108-113. doi: 10.1136/emermed-2021-212294. Epub 2022 Sep 30. PMID: 36180168."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62165"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16172"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16172"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/48614004-d5ab-4a61-a318-615404b990af.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/48614004-d5ab-4a61-a318-615404b990af.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":353}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id